text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Accents of Sign Language%0a%0a:Author: BrandonN%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDifferent cultures and types of signers have accents%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aUnlike spoken language, sign language takes on different accents and is flexible with the meanings. This language seems to be so flexible that families on their own can develop accents only distinguished by them. For example, a family, who lived remotely in Alaska, developed their own unique accent which also had idioms. I have always found it surprising how ASL users can develop accents that are understandable among different people/cultures. For example, the speed of certain signers is a small detail that can indicate information about someone's culture. Another difference among signers concerning accents is the difference between completely deaf signers and those who are able to hear and sign. I have no experience with sign language but I find it amazing that small details can be passed on through the style of a persons' signing. A question that I have for users of sign language is if there is ever an accent or dialect that is not understood between users. As we have gone over throughout the semester, culture is important and that drives different dialects and accents. I think this may be more difficult for signers but this seems to be another topic that can be looked over more in-depth. %0a%0alinks: https://publishingsolutionsgroup.com/blog/dont-miss-the-signs-regional-accents-in-sign-language/%0ahttps://www.handspeak.com/study/index.php?id=3%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-024421-360410#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Different types of sign language in the US %0a-> - MindeeL%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAfter reading the article, I wanted to look more into the difference in accent between completely deaf signers and signers who are hearing. I found out that in addition to ASL (which is used by the Deaf community and has its own grammar and syntax), there is a common type of signing called PSE which is usually used to communicate between hearing and deaf people. PSE stands for pigdin signed english and it follows English grammar but uses words/vocabulary from ASL. I wonder if the accent of hearing people when they sign is influenced from their knowledge of spoken english and looks more similar to PSE than "accent-less/standard" ASL. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-024421-360410#%0a#foxbegin 210508-222736-763810#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Distinguish accents and dialects in sign language %0a-> - yuluz%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aOne question that intrigues me a lot regarding sign language if how we distinguish between accents and dialects. I think after reading and researching, I would say that if there is stylistic difference but mutual intelligibility between variations of sign languages, then we can consider them to be different accents. While if there are certain words or grammars that differ but the intelligibility is retained to a large extent, then we would consider those variations as dialects.  %0a%0aJust to give an example of dialects in sign language: some researchers consider Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language as dialects of the British sign Language because they use the same grammar, the same manual alphabet, and much of the same vocabulary, so their mutual intelligibility is retaine. Nevertheless, there are also differences between these variations, like New Zealand Sign Language having signs for Māori words. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-222736-763810#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
